	     <br clear=all><small>Posted @ Tue, Aug 27th 6:05 PM 2002</small></td></tr>
	     <tr><td valign=top id=fs8 class=mform><span id=notbold>By:</span> <a href=poster.html?user=128514><span id=Scholar>Banvaren</span></a><br><b><span id=Scholar>Scholar</span></b><br><span id=notbold>72 posts<br><span id=notbold>Score</span>: Excellent [5.00]</td><td valign=top class=mform width=100%><p>ANSWER 1: Yes you will need to lull all mobs that you do not want to come on the pull. Also, a lulled mob will still come if the one you pulled runs&nbsp;&nbsp;close enough to him. Lull only reduces aggro radius, it does not eliminate it. So if there are three mobs in a group, cast lull on the two farthest away from you, casting on the farthest one first. If they stick, pull the one closest to you and he will not run within the aggro adius of the lulled mobs. You are right, getting lull to stack is difficult. I am convinced that Charisma affects spells like lull/root/stun, so a low CHA will hurt.<br><br>ANSWER 2: Stuns do interupt casters and are a Paladin's best way to draw aggro. The cast time on stuns are pretty much the fastest cast times in the game and will not change. Evocation skill only affects fizzle rate. Mobs level, mobs resists, your level and your CHA affect whether or not the stuns are resisted.  </p>&nbsp;<br>Banvaren Holybane<br>65 Paladin <br>Povar Server<br><br><a href="http://www.magelo.com/eq_view_profile.html?num=584233" target=_new>http://www.magelo.com/eq_view_profile.html?num=584233</a></td></td></tr>
